Is it annoying in the way that it keeps being brought up? Why Harry spends
so much time worrying about it?

If so, you have to know by now that all 7 books have pretty much all been
from Harry's point of view. In this case, that's how he feels - that people
are risking their lives for him out of a sense of loyalty.

I'm sure Harry's closest friends (Ron, Hermione, Neville, Luna, etc.) do
feel this way, though what Harry never &quot;gets&quot; is that it's not up to him
what other people do, or what their motivation is - that's what drives him
into such angst, he doesn't get that they're doing it because they want to,
not because they feel the need to prove any loyalty.

The wider Wizarding World is indeed helping Harry for the reason you
mention - he's a tool against Voldy.

They believe this because of the reports in The Daily Prophet of The
Prophecy, and they need &quot;hope&quot; in these Dark Times. Harry winds up being
what Fudge &amp; Scrimgeour wanted - a symbol. Though Harry standing &quot;alone&quot;
(not with the Ministry) is what, I think, really rallied the People - that
he was not only destined to defeat LV, but he was brave enough to also fight
The System that ultimately fails them.

