No, I don't think that's the case.  I agree that in the real world,
Snape's fear of Voldemort would have to be taken into consideration.
But in the books, it isn't even mentioned.  Rowling makes it pretty
clear that Snape is motivated strictly by Lily, and in her absence, by
a desire to keep her son alive.

And yes, he still hates Harry.  He wants to protect him strictly
because he is Lily's son.  It is a favor for Lily, not for Harry.
Snape makes that clear in the scene where he shows Dumbledore his
patronus.

My point is that Snape was more obsessed with keeping Lily's son alive
than almost anyone else.  As the old saying goes: whooda thunkit?
